A short thread on details and lore on the "Reply of the Zaporozhian Cossacks" painting, there is surprisingly much going on

The basic story can easily be found on Wikipedia, read it if you have not, I will talk about complimentary stuff

Most of the cossacks were based on real people, friends of Repin (the artist)

The scribe writing the letter is based on the Russian historian and archeologist Dmytro Yavornytsky, of course with a more traditional "bowl" hairstyle

The ataman (title for leader/warchief) Ivan Sirko, the person dictating the letter, a very successful historical figure, who was also an alleged magus (quite unknown info here) was based on Mikhail Dragomirov, a Russian military general, famous for being witty and of good humor

Vladimir Gilyarovsky posed for the white-hat wearing large cossack

He allegedly also has posed for a painting as Taras Bulba, a character from a Nikolai Gogol novel, another cossack

The reason this lone cossack is shirtless (except that Eastern men do not fear the winer cold) is that he was the table's card dealer, and at that time it was a custom for card dealers to be shirtless, as to show they are not cheating by hiding extra cards in their sleeves
Here is a reconstruction of Ivan Sirko's actual skull/head, which is pretty close to the painting's version, which was based on the general, same phenotype pretty much lol
A final detail to conclude the quick thread, there is a dog near the men's feet that no one seems to notice as it kind of blends with the dirt, but it's there and kind of cute
